      "subjectFrames": [
        "artists_makers",
        "teachers_educators",
        "communities_publics"
      ],
      "excerpt": "STUDIES in Art Education A Journal of Issues and Research 1986,27 (3) 109·114 Copyright by The National Art Education Association To Eat Your Cake and Have It Too: A Response to Beyond Creating Vincent Lanier University of Arizona Despite a generally progressive professional orientation toward Discipline-Based Art Educ",
      "quotes": [
        {
          "text": "Early in the section the writer (or writers) establishes the rationale for having art in the school under the subtitle \"Why Art Education?\" A primary goal of education is to enable children to develop their minds and intellectual capabilities, using all forms of creative intelligence as means for achieving this goal.",
          "tags": [
            "cognitive",
            "creative",
            "developmental",
            "creative_capacity",
            "mind_concepts",
            "pedagogical_institutions"
          ],
          "families": [
            "types",
            "perspectives",
            "definitions",
            "locations"
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "A phrase reminiscent of the language of creativity, the idea of coping with ambiguity shares all those problems plaguing other developmental ideas with which the history of art education is littered.",
          "tags": [
            "communicative",
            "creative",
            "developmental",
            "language",
            "creative_capacity",
            "interpretive_meaning"
          ],
          "families": [
            "types",
            "perspectives",
            "signals",
            "definitions",
            "recognition"
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "The school's curriculum is currently heavily weighted toward a rule- governed view of learning; there is a correct and incorrect answer to each question raised, the teacher knows the correct answer, the student's task is to get it right.",
          "tags": [
            "pedagogy",
            "teacherhood",
            "pedagogical_institutions",
            "teachers_educators"
          ],
          "families": [
            "perspectives",
            "signals",
            "locations",
            "subjects"
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "All works of visual art are visual images (although some contemporary styles such as Conceptual Art have begun to move away from that dependence), but all visual images are not works of visual art.",
          "tags": [
            "cognitive",
            "vision_perception",
            "mind_concepts"
          ],
          "families": [
            "types",
            "locations"
          ]
        }
      ],
