      "subjectFrames": [
        "artists_makers",
        "children_students",
        "communities_publics"
      ],
      "excerpt": "Copyright 200 I by the NationalAn Education Association in Art Education AJournal of Issues and Research 2001, 42(4), 372-375 Correspondence concerningthis response should be addressed to the author at The Florida State University, Department of Art Education, School of Visual Arts and Dance, 126 MCH, Tallahassee, FL 3",
      "quotes": [
        {
          "text": "My \"instrumental\" claim that art making involves higher order thinking and the development of intelligent perceptual and conceptual abilities is not new, but it is a rationale that can be sold to the public for the teaching and evaluation ofart learning in schools.",
          "tags": [
            "cognitive",
            "pedagogy",
            "judgment_critique",
            "making_performance",
            "participation_relation",
            "mind_concepts"
          ],
          "families": [
            "types",
            "perspectives",
            "recognition",
            "locations",
            "subjects"
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "Dorn Florida StateUniversity Ted Bracey's criticism of my book Mind in Art: Cognitive Foundations in Art Education finds fault with my views on artists, art, philosophy, psy- chology, mind-body relationships and with my failure to elucidate a theory of Art Education.",
          "tags": [
            "cognitive",
            "communicative",
            "philosophy",
            "interpretive_meaning",
            "judgment_critique",
            "mind_concepts"
          ],
          "families": [
            "types",
            "perspectives",
            "definitions",
            "recognition",
            "locations",
            "subjects"
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "More importantly, perhaps, Bracey aims a good deal of his criticism at my claim that art making is an intelligent activity.",
          "tags": [
            "communicative",
            "philosophy",
            "interpretive_meaning",
            "judgment_critique",
            "making_performance"
          ],
          "families": [
            "types",
            "perspectives",
            "definitions",
            "recognition"
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "Bracey's acceptance of the view that art is a language and of Morris Weitz's (Witgenstein's student) claim that no theory of art is possible contradicts his expectation that I should have developed a theory.",
          "tags": [
            "communicative",
            "philosophy",
            "language",
            "interpretive_meaning",
            "children_students"
          ],
          "families": [
            "types",
            "perspectives",
            "signals",
            "definitions",
            "subjects"
          ]
        }
      ],
